Here is a concise breakdown of how that flowchart operates:

1. Enter for loop (The Starting Point)
This is the "Start" circle at the top. It represents the moment your code reaches the for statement. At this stage, the computer looks at the sequence (like a list of names or a range of numbers) and prepares to start from the beginning.

2. Check for last item (The Decision Diamond)
The diamond is the "brain" of the loop. Every time the loop starts a new round, it asks a question: "Is there another item left in this sequence?" This is the guard that prevents the loop from running forever. It checks the items one by one in order.

3. The "True" Path: If there is an item...
If the answer to the diamond's question is Yes, the flow moves downward: Execute loop body: The computer performs the actual task you wrote (like printing a value or doing a calculation).
The Feedback Loop: Notice the arrow pointing from the bottom box back up to the diamond. Once the task is done for one item, it goes right back to the top to check for the next item.

4. The "False" Path: If no item is remaining... Eventually, the computer will reach the end of the list. When the diamond asks "Is there another item?" and the answer is No:

